---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { logoSet } from "../lib/media";
import { defaultDescription, defaultOgImage, siteName, toAbsoluteUrl } from "../lib/seo";

const logo = logoSet();
const description = "About rajintalksalot, Rajin Khan's visual archive for media dives, recommendations, tech notes, monthly recaps, personal reflections, and original work.";
const structuredData = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "AboutPage",
  name: "About rajintalksalot",
  description,
  url: toAbsoluteUrl("/about/"),
  image: toAbsoluteUrl(defaultOgImage),
  isPartOf: {
    "@type": "WebSite",
    name: siteName,
    url: toAbsoluteUrl("/")
  },
  author: {
    "@type": "Person",
    name: "Rajin Khan",
    url: "https://rajinkhan.com"
  }
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title="rk - About"
  description={description || defaultDescription}
  canonicalPath="/about/"
  bodyClass="about-body"
  structuredData={structuredData}
>
  <section class="about-shell" aria-labelledby="about-heading">
    <h1 id="about-heading" class="sr-only">About rajintalksalot</h1>
    <div class="about-mark" aria-hidden="true">
      <picture>
        <source srcset={logo.avif} type="image/avif" />
        <source srcset={logo.webp} type="image/webp" />
        <img src={logo.fallback} width={logo.width} height={logo.height} alt="" />
      </picture>
    </div>

    <div class="about-copy">
      <p class="eyebrow">about the archive</p>
      <p>
        I started <strong>rajintalksalot</strong> on Instagram because it was the
        easiest place to put thoughts into motion: image, caption, post, move on.
        Also because I really fucking talk a lot.
        But at some point, the format didn't cut it for what I wanted
        the pieces to do.
      </p>
      <p>
        I didn't just want a blog that listed posts. I wanted the interface to
        matter too. The scrolling, the stacks, the pauses, the glows, all that 
        fancy UI/UX bullshit, sure, but really it was simpler than that: I wanted 
        the site to feel like the work itself.
      </p>
      <p>
        Instagram is great for momentum, but terrible at letting a post breathe.
        So I went to the drawing board and built what I wanted myself. Same feeling, same visual-first
        instinct, but less feed, more exhibition.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Media Dives</strong> is where I overthink films, shows, albums,
        paintings, and anything else that refuses to leave my head. <strong>Not
        Gatekeeping</strong> is for things worth passing on. <strong>ByteLine</strong>
        is for tools, stacks, tech, and projects. <strong>From the Vault</strong>
        is for my own work (coming soon, probably). <strong>Monologue</strong> is exactly what it sounds like.
      </p>
      <p>
        And then there are the monthly <strong>In Words</strong> posts: little
        recaps of what I've been into, what stuck, what changed the mood, and
        what somehow became important for no obvious reason. The site keeps the
        beat of the original posts, but gives the words and images room to
        do their thing.
      </p>
      <p>
        I post whatever I want, whenever I feel like it.
        I don't follow any schedule.
        Hope you find stuff you like.
      </p>
      <a
        class="about-return"
        href="/"
        data-site-fade-link
        data-site-fade-key="rajintalksalot-archive-entry"
      >
        Back to blog
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
